    "id": "baharna",
    "name": "Baharna",
    "nameAr": "بُحارنة",
    "ethnicity": "arab",
    "religion": "shia",
    "identityType": "ethnoreligious",
    "preIslamicOrigins": "Ancient pre-Islamic population including partially-Christianized Arabs, Aramaic-speaking agriculturalists, Persian Zoroastrians, and Jews. Archaeological evidence shows Parthian artifacts and Christian churches from 4th-8th centuries CE.",
    "populationEstimate": "Most Bahraini citizens are Baharna, with populations throughout Eastern Arabia and diaspora communities",
    "traditionalEconomy": "Agriculture, handcrafts including weaving with palm leaves (mats, baskets, fans) and pottery",
    "originNarrative": "Debated origins with multiple theories. Western scholars believe they originate from Bahrain's ancient pre-Islamic population consisting of partially-Christianized Arabs, Aramaic-speaking agriculturalists, Persian Zoroastrians, and Jews. Most families claim descent from Rab'ia tribe, particularly Abd al-Qays (Nestorian Christians), Anizah, Bakr Bin Wail, Banu Tamim, and Al-Azd from Yemen.",
    "keyTension": "Distinguished from other ethnic groups like Sunni Arabs (Al Arab/Bani Utbah) and Bahraini-Iranians (Ajam). Inhabited region before arrival of Banu Utbah in 18th century.",
    "description": "Arabic-speaking ethnoreligious group mostly of Shia Muslim background, indigenous to the historical region of Bahrain. Regarded by some scholars as the original inhabitants of Eastern Arabia.",
